De Michele, Leonede(I-MILAN); Mauceri, Giancarlo(I-GENO) 
$H\sp p$ multipliers on stratified groups. 
Ann. Mat. Pura Appl. (4) 148 (1987), 353--366.

Suppose $G$ is a stratified Lie group of homogeneous dimension $Q$,
${\cal L}$ 
is a sub-Laplacian on $G$, and $M$ is a bounded Borel function on $(0,\infty)$.  A. Hulanicki and  E. M.
Stein \ref[see the reviewer and Stein, Hardy spaces on homogeneous groups, Princeton Univ. Press, Princeton, N.J., 1982; MR 84h:43027] proved that the operator $M({\cal L})$ is bounded on
$H^p(G)$ for $Q/(Q+r)<p<\infty$, and in particular on $L^p(G)$ for $1<p<\infty$, provided that $M$ is of class $C^{(s)}$ and $|t^jM^{(j)}(t)|\le C$ for $j\le s$ where $s>r+(3Q/2)+2$. The
authors obtain the same conclusion under the weaker hypothesis that $M$ satisfies an appropriate Lipschitz-Besov condition of order $s$ where $s>r+(Q/2)+1$. This hypothesis is nearly optimal;
when $G=\bold R^n$ the sharp condition on $s$ is known to be $s>r+(n/2)$. The proof exploits the atomic and molecular characterizations of $H^p$ spaces.

                                   Reviewed by Gerald B. Folland 


-----------------------------------------

\vspace{.4in}

Kawazoe, Takeshi(J-KEIOES) 
A characterization of the Poisson kernel on the classical real rank one symmetric spaces. 
Tokyo J. Math. 15 (1992), no. 2, 365--379.


Introduction: "Let $G$ be a connected real rank-one semisimple Lie
group and $G=KAN$ an Iwasawa decomposition 
for $G$. Let $\mathfrak{g}=\mf{ k}+\mf{a}+\mf{ n}$ denote the corresponding Iwasawa decomposition for the Lie algebra $\mf{ g}$ of $G$. We define $H(x)$ $(x\in G)$ as the unique element in
$\mf{ a}$ such that $x\in K\exp H(x)N$ and put $\rho(H)={\rm tr}({\rm
ad}(H)\vert \sb \mf{ n})$ for $H\in\mf{ a}$. 
Let $M$ be the centralizer of $A$ in $K$
and $\Delta$ the Laplace-Beltrami operator on $G/K$. Then the Poisson kernel $P\colon G/K\times K/M\to\bold R$ is given by
$P(gK,kM)=\exp(-2\rho(H(g\sp {-1}k)))$, and for each $s\in\bold C$, $P\sp s$ is an eigenfunction of $\Delta$ with eigenvalue $\lambda\sb s$, say. Then our
problem can be stated as follows. Problem: Let us suppose that a real-valued, $C\sp 2$ function $F$ on $G/K$ satisfies the following conditions: (1) $\Delta
F=0$, (2) $\Delta F\sp 2=\lambda\sb 2F\sp 2$, (3) $F(eK)=1$. Then is $F$ determined by $F(gK)=P(gK,kM)$ for an element $kM$ in $K/M$? 

"When $G={\rm SO}\sb 0(n,1)$ and ${\rm SU}(n,1)$, affirmative answers were obtained elsewhere [M. Chipot, P. Eymard and T. Tahani, in Symposia
Mathematica, Vol. XXIX (Cortona, 1984), 111--129, Sympos. Math., 29, Academic Press, New York, 1987; MR 89i:43007; T. Tahani, "Fonctions propres
de l'operateur de Laplace-Beltrami dans les boules hyperboliques reelle ou complex", Thesis, Univ. Nancy I, Vandoeuvre-les-Nancy, 1985; per bibl.; T.
Kawazoe and T. Tahani, Tokyo J. Math. 11 (1988), no. 1, 37--55; MR 89h:22016]. However, their arguments are slightly dependent on each circumstance
of the group. Therefore, it is worthwhile to give another proof which treats the problem uniformly, and apply it to the case of ${\rm Sp}(n,1)$. Now let $G$ be
one of the classical real rank one semisimple Lie groups: ${\rm SO}\sb 0(n,1)$, ${\rm SU}(n,1)$ and ${\rm Sp}(n,1)$. In $§4$ we prove that if a real-valued
$C\sp 2$ function $F$ on $G/K$ satisfies (1)--(3) and (4) $F$ is $M$-invariant, then $F$ is determined by the Poisson kernels. In $§5$ we try to remove this
additional condition. Although we can remove it in the cases ${\rm SO}\sb 0(n,1)$ and ${\rm SU}(n,1)$, we need an assumption for the case of ${\rm
Sp}(n,1)$, which can be stated as follows. We first identify $G/K$ $(G={\rm Sp}(n,1)$ and $K={\rm Sp}(n)\times{\rm Sp}(1))$ with the unit ball $D\sp n$ in
$\bold H\sp n$ where $\bold H$ is the quaternions, and denote the standard coordinates on $\bold H\sp n$ by $w\sb 1,w\sb 2,\cdots,w\sb n$. Since $F$ is
real analytic from (1), $F$ has a homogeneous expansion $F=\sum\sp \infty\sb {N=0}F\sb N$, where each $F\sb N$ is a homogeneous polynomial with
degree $N$. Then we easily see that there exists an element $k\sb 0$ in $K$ such that the rotation $F\sb {k\sb 0}$ of $F$ defined by $F\sb {k\sb
0}(w)=F(k\sb 0·w)$ $(w\in D\sp n)$ satisfies $(F\sb {k\sb 0})\sb 1(w)=(2n+1)(w\sb 1+\overline w\sb 1)$ (see (5.5)). Then the assumption which we need to
obtain the affirmative answer to the above problem is the following: (5) $F\sb {k\sb 0}(cw\sb 1,w\sb 2,\cdots,w\sb n)=F\sb {k\sb 0}(w\sb 1c,w\sb 2,\cdots,
w\sb n)$ for all $c$ in $\bold H$, i.e., $F\sb {k\sb 0}$ is a function of $w\sb 1+\overline w\sb 1$, $\vert w\sb 1\vert \sp 2$ and $w\sb s+\overline w\sb s$,
$w\sb si-i\overline w\sb s$, $w\sb sj-j\overline w\sb s$, $w\sb sk-k\overline w\sb s$ $(2\leq s\leq n)$. Then if $F$ satisfies (1)--(3) and (5), $F(gK)$ is
determined by the Poisson kernel $P(gK,k\sb 0M)$. Since $\bold R$ and $\bold C$ are abelian, the condition corresponding to (5) in the cases of $G={\rm
SO}\sb 0(n,1)$ and ${\rm SU}(n,1)$ holds automatically, and thus there is no need to assume (5)."

\vspace{.3in}

Kawazoe, Takeshi(J-KEIO); Tahani, Taoufiq(F-LILL) 
Correction to: "A characterization of the Poisson kernel associated with ${\rm SU}(1,n)$" [Tokyo J. Math. 11 (1988), no. 1, 37--55; MR 89h:22016].

Tokyo J. Math. 17 (1994), no. 2, 495--497.
22E30 (43A85)

Jacques Faraut:

In the paper cited in the heading the authors stated that a real
function on the Riemannian symmetric space $G/K$, $G={\rm SU}(1,n)$, 
which satisfies
$DF=0$, $DF^2=\lambda F^2$, $F(eK)=1$, where $D$ is the Laplace operator, is equal to the Poisson kernel $P(gK,kM)$ for some point $kM$ on the
boundary $K/M$. At some point of the proof there was a mistake in the computation of an integral. The idea of the new proof they propose is different, and
could be extended to the case of ${\rm Sp}(1,n)$. 

\vspace{.3in}

Kawazoe, Takeshi(J-KEIO) 
Atomic Hardy spaces on semisimple Lie groups. 
Japan. J. Math. (N.S.) 11 (1985), no. 2, 293--343.

The author gives a definition of Hardy spaces $H^1_{q,s}$ of $K$-invariant functions on a rank-one symmetric space $G/K$ of noncompact type. To some
extent he follows the lines of a paper by  R. R. Coifman and 
G. Weiss \ref[Bull. 
Amer. Math. Soc. 83 (1977), no. 4, 569--645;] to
define $(q,s)$-atoms as the building blocks of $H^1_{q,s}$, even though $G/K$ is not a space of homogeneous type. The fact that only atoms centered at
the origin are used makes these spaces too small to be considered analogues of the classical Hardy spaces. For instance, the definition proposed here,
when applied to the Euclidean symmetric space $ R^n\rtimes {\rm SO}(n)/{\rm SO}(n)$, does not lead to the space of radial functions in $H^1( R^n)$.
However, a characterization of $H^1 _{\infty,0}$ is given in terms of nondecreasing $L^1$ dominating functions and various results are given about the
boundedness from $H^1_{q,s}$ to $L^1$ of maximal operators, Fourier multipliers and pseudodifferential operators.


\vspace{.3in}
 Kawazoe, Takeshi Atomic Hardy spaces on semisimple Lie groups. Noncommutative harmonic analysis and Lie groups (Marseille-Luminy, 1985),
  189--197, Lecture Notes in Math., 1243, Springer, Berlin, 1987.
Kawazoe, Takeshi 
Atomic Hardy spaces on semisimple Lie groups. 
Noncommutative harmonic analysis and Lie groups (Marseille-Luminy, 1985), 189--197, 
Lecture Notes in Math., 1243, 
Springer, Berlin, 1987. 

Gerald B. Folland:

The author defines $H^1$ atoms and molecules in the context of $K$-bi-invariant functions on a semisimple Lie group. He shows that an appropriate grand
maximal function is bounded from atomic $H^1$ to $L^1$ and that molecules have atomic decompositions. 

{For the entire collection see MR 88b:22001.}

\vspace{.3in}

$KA$-wavelets on semisimple Lie groups and quasi-orthogonality of matrix coefficients. 
Infinite dimensional harmonic analysis (Kyoto, 1999), 238--252, 
Gräbner, Altendorf, 2000. 

This is an excellent article connecting integral wavelet transforms
and representations of semisimple Lie groups. 
Emphasis is placed on the group
$G:= {\rm SU}(1,1)$, the weighted Bergman spaces $\mathcal{H}_h$ and
the holomorphic discrete series of $G$. 
More precisely, the author proves that
there are a $\varphi\in\mathcal{H}:={\rm Cal}\,\mathcal{ H}_{1/2}$ and a
representation $T$ of $G$ over $\mathcal{ H}$ 
such that $$f=\text{const}·\int_K dk\int_A\langle
f, T(ka_t)\varphi\rangle T(ka_t)\varphi\sinh2t\,dt,$$ for all $f\in\mathcal{ H}$, a finite dimensional subspace, where $\langle,\rangle$ denotes the scalar product in
${\rm Cal}\,\mathcal{ H}$, and $K$ and $A$ denote the groups of Euclidean and hyperbolic rotations, respectively. 

The article will be useful for a graduate course in wavelet and group theory. 



Wavelet transforms associated to a principal series representation of semisimple Lie groups. I, II. 
Proc. Japan Acad. Ser. A Math. Sci. 71 (1995), no. 7, 154--157, 158--160.

 "We investigate a transform associated to a principal series representation of noncompact semisimple Lie groups and we obtain a
generalization of the Grossmann-Morlet transform and the Calderón identity. A transform associated to the analytic continuation of the holomorphic discrete
series and its limit will be treated in a forthcoming paper \ref[T. Kawazoe, "A transform associated to the analytic continuation of the holomorphic discrete
series of a semisimple Lie group", manuscript; per bibl.]. 

"Let $G$ be a noncompact connected semisimple Lie group with finite center and $P=MAN$ a parabolic subgroup of $G$. Let $\pi_\lambda={\rm
Ind}^G_P(1\otimes e^\lambda\otimes 1) (\lambda\in {a}^*_ C)$ denote a principal series representation of $G$ and $(\pi_\lambda,L^2(\overline{N},
e^{-2{\rm Im}\,\lambda(H(\overline n))}d\overline n))$ $(\overline N=\theta(N))$ the noncompact picture of $\pi_\lambda$. Let $\sigma_\omega$ denote an
irreducible unitary representation of $\overline N$ corresponding to $\omega\in\overline{ n}{}^*_ C$ and $(S,ds)$ a subset of $MA$ with measure $ds$.
In Part I we assume that there exists a $\phi\in\mathcal{ S}'(\overline N)$
satisfying the following admissible 
condition: for all $\omega\in V'_T$
$$\sigma_\omega(\phi)\sigma_\omega(\phi)^*=n_\phi(\omega)I,\qquad{\rm
i}$$ 

$$0<\int_S n_\phi({\rm Ad}(s)\omega)ds=c_{S,\phi}<\infty,\qquad{\rm
ii}$$ 
where $c_{S,\phi}$ is independent of $\omega$. Then for all such
$\phi$ we can deduce the inversion 
formula: $$f(x)=c^{-1}_{S,\phi}\iint_{\overline{N}\times
S}\langle
f,\pi_{-i\rho}(\overline{n}s)\phi\rangle\pi_{-i\rho}(\overline{n}s)\phi(x)d\overline{n}ds\ 
\forall f\in\mathcal{ S}(\overline N),$$ where $\langle·,·\rangle$ is the
inner product of $L^2(\overline N)$. A number of well-known examples of wavelet transforms arise from this scheme through the explicit form of $\phi$.
However, in the case of $G={\rm SL}(n+2,\bold R) (n\geq 1)$ and $\overline N\cong H_n$, the $(2n+1)$-dimensional Heisenberg group, the above formula
does not cover the three examples constructed by C. Kalisa and B. Torrésani \ref[see Ann. Inst. H. Poincaré Phys. Théor. 59 (1993), no. 2, 201--236; MR
95i:22033]. Therefore, in order to obtain a widespread application we need to generalize this formula."


Kawazoe, Takeshi(J-KEIOE) 
Wavelet transform associated to an induced representation of ${\rm SL}(n+2,\bold R)$. (English. English, French summary) 
Ann. Inst. H. Poincaré Phys. Théor. 65 (1996), no. 1, 1--13.
22E70 (43A80 81R30)

G. C. Bohnké:

Since the paper of A. Grossmann, J. Morlet and T. Paul \ref[J. Math. Phys. 26 (1985), no. 10, 2473--2479; MR 86k:22013] much work on the "continuous
wavelet transform" has been done, more or less in the spirit of Lie group theory. Here the author constructs the wavelet transform via the induced
representation machinery in the ${\rm SL}(n+2,\bold R)$ case. 

From the summary: "Let $G={\rm SL}(n+2,\bold R)$ and let $P=MAN$ be a parabolic subgroup of $G$ such that $N$ is isomorphic to the Heisenberg group
$H_n$. Let $1\otimes e^\lambda\otimes 1$ be a representation of $P$ and let $\pi_\lambda=\break {\rm Ind}_P^G(1\otimes e^\lambda\otimes 1)$ be the
induced representation of $G$ acting on $L^2(H_n)$. In this paper we
obtain a condition on $\lambda$ and
 $\psi\in \mathcal{ S}'(H_n)$ for which the matrix
coefficients $\langle f,\pi_\lambda(g)\psi\rangle_{L^2(H_n)}$ are square-integrable on a subgroup $\overline NA_1\simeq H_n\times \bold R$ of $G$ and
$\|f\|^2_{L^2(H_n)}=c\iint_{\overline NA_1}|\langle f,\pi_\lambda(\overline na_1)\psi\rangle_{L^2(H_n)}|^2d\overline nda_1\text{ for all } f\in \mathcal{ S}(H_n).$" 

Examples are given for several admissible functions $\psi (h)=\alpha(p,q)\beta(t)$, $h=(p,q,t)\in H_n\approx\bold R^n\times\bold R^n\times \bold R$. (In the
case of ${\rm SL}(2,\bold R)$, the function $\alpha(p,q)$ is disregarded and one recovers the classical wavelet transform associated to the affine "$ax+b$"
group.) 

The author also announces further results in a more general setting which will appear in forthcoming papers.


-------------------------------------------

Kenig, C. E.; Stanton, R. J.; Tomas, P. A. Divergence of eigenfunction expansions. J. Funct. Anal. 46 (1982), no. 1, 28--44.


The authors prove transplantation theorems for families of commuting differential operators on a smooth paracompact $n$-dimensional manifold $\Omega$. These allow us to deduce from uniform
boundedness as $R\rightarrow\infty$ of operators on $L^p(\Omega)$ of the form $Q_Km_R(P_1,\cdots,P_k)Q_K$, boundedness of the operator $m(p_1(x,\xi),\cdots,p_k(x,\xi))$ on $L^p(
R^n)$. (Here, $m\colon R^k\rightarrow R$ is a bounded Borel function, $\{P_1,\cdots,P_k\}$ a commuting set of symmetric differential operators with selfadjoint extensions to $L^2(\Omega)$,
$p_j$ is the principal symbol of $P_j$, $K$ a subset of $\Omega$ of positive measure, $x$ a point of density of $K$, and $Q_K\colon L^2\rightarrow L^2\colon f\rightarrow\chi_Kf$. If $m_j$ is
the degree of $P_j$, then $m_R(x_1,\cdots,x_k)$ is defined to be $m(R^{-m_1}x_1,\cdots,R^{-m_k}x_k)$.) The method of proof is based on a theorem of B. S. Mityagin [ Linear operators and
approximation, II\/ (Oberwolfach, 1974), pp. 521--530, Birkhäuser, Basel, 1974] combined with a theorem of Rellich's on the convergence of spectral expansions. These techniques
are also used to give weak type $(p,p)$ results. 

The transplantation theorems are then combined with results of Kenig and Tomas [Bull. Amer. Math. Soc. (N.S.) 1 (1979), no. 4, 694--697; MR 81g:42019] to give negative results on summability
methods for a noncompact semisimple Lie group $G$. For example, if $m$ is a bounded Borel function on $ R^l$, not identically zero, such that $m(x)=O(|x|^{-\varepsilon})$ for some
$\varepsilon>0$, and $S_R$ denotes the summability method on $G$ defined by $m$, then for each $p\neq 2$, there is $f\in L^p(G)$ so that $\|S_Rf-f\|_p\rightarrow 0$. If $1<p<2$, then for
some $f\in L^p(G)$, $\sup_R|S_Rf|=\infty$ almost everywhere. Another application: Projection onto the discrete series of $\text{SL}(2, R)$ is $L^p$ bounded if and only if $p=2$. (This answers a
question of Stein.)



----by A. H. Dooley 



-----------------------------------


Cowling, Michael 
The Kunze-Stein phenomenon. 
Ann. Math. (2) 107 (1978), no. 2, 209--234.

Let $G$ be a connected semisimple Lie group with finite center. In this interesting paper the author studies the convolution of functions on $G$. The
following theorem is proved: if $1\leq p<2$, then $L^p(G)*L^2(G)\subseteq L^2(G)$. Special cases of this result were obtained by several authors.

-------------------------------------

Kunze, R. A.; Stein, E. M. 
Uniformly bounded representations and harmonic analysis of the $2\times 2$ real unimodular group. 
Amer. J. Math. 82 1960 1--62.

This paper contains a remarkably detailed study of representations of and harmonic analysis on the group $G$ of $2\times 2$ real unimodular matrices. The
continuous irreducible unitary representations of $G$ were found long
ago by Gel'fand and Neumark 
[Acad. Sci. USSR J. Phys. 10 (1946),
93--94; MR 8, 132; Izv. Akad. Nauk SSSR Ser. Mat. 11 (1947), 411--504; MR 9, 495] and independently by V. Bargmann [Ann. of Math. (2) 48 (1947),
568--640; MR 9, 133]. Plancherel's formula for this group was established by Harish-Chandra [Proc. Nat. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. 38 (1952), 337--342; MR 13,
820]. To explain the results of this paper, some notation is needed. 
A generic element $g$ of $G$ is a matrix 
$\left( \begin{array}{cc}
 a & b \\ 
c & d 
\end{array} \right)$;
$ad-bc=1$; $a,b,c,d\in R$. For $g\in G$, $x\in R$, and $s\in C$, let $\phi^+(g,x,s)=|bx+d|^{2s-2}$, $\phi^-(g,x,s)=\text{sgn}(bx+d)\phi^+(g,x,s)$. For $g\in G$
and $x\in R$, let $g(x)=(ax+c)/(bx+d)$. For complex-valued functions $f$ on $ R$, let $$ (v^±(g,s)f)(x)=\phi^±(g,x,s)f\circ g(x). $$ The linear operators
$v^±(g,s)$ obviously provide representations of $G$. The representations $g\rightarrow v^±(g,\frac 1{2}+it) (t\in R)$ acting on $L_2( R)$ are continuous,
irreducible and unitary, and are called the two principal continuous series. The representations $g\rightarrow v^+(g,\sigma) (0<\sigma<{\textstyle\frac
1{2}})$, acting on the Hilbert space $H_\sigma$ of functions on $ R$ with inner product $$ a_\sigma\int_{ R}\int_{ R}f(x)\overline{f(y)}|x-y|^{-2\sigma}\,dxdy,
$$ are also continuous, irreducible and unitary, and are called the complementary series. Finally, there are two discrete series of continuous irreducible
unitary representations of $G$; these play only a minor rôle in the present paper. 

A main result of the paper is that the representations of the principal and complementary series can be analytically continued into the set $\{s\in C\colon
0<\text{Re}(s)<1\}= S$ in the following sense. There are a separable
Hilbert space $\mathcal{H}$ and
 representations $g\rightarrow U^±(g,s)$ of $G$ on $\mathcal{H}$
such that: (1) $g\rightarrow U^±(g,s)$ is a continuous representation of $G$ for each $s\in S$; (2) $g\rightarrow U^±(g,{\textstyle\frac 1{2}}+it) (t\in R)$ is
unitarily equivalent to the representation $g\rightarrow v^±(g,{\textstyle\frac 1{2}}+it)$ of the principal continuous series; (3) $g\rightarrow U^+(g,\sigma)
(0<\sigma<{\textstyle\frac 1{2}})$ is unitarily equivalent to the representation $g\rightarrow v^+(g,\sigma)$ of the complementary series; (4) for $g$ fixed in
$G$, and $\xi,\eta$ fixed in $\mathcal{ H}$, the function
$s\rightarrow\langle U^±(g,s)\xi,\eta\rangle$ is analytic 
in $S$; 
$$ \sup\{\|U^±(g,\sigma+it)\|\colon g\in
G\}\leq A_{\sigma,\varepsilon}(1+|t|)^{|\sigma-1/2|(1+\varepsilon)}
\qquad(5) $$ 
for $0<\sigma<1$ and $\varepsilon>0$, where $A_{\sigma,\varepsilon}>0$ and is
bounded on every interval $0<\alpha\leq\sigma\leq\beta<1$. 

The authors use the representations $U^±(g,s) (s\in S)$ to obtain a complete analogue of the Hausdorff-Young theorem for $G$. A bounded linear operator
$A$ on the separable Hilbert space $\mathcal{ H}$ is in $\mathcal{ B}_p (1\leq p<\infty)$ if the non-negative operator $(A^*A)^{1/2}=|A|$ has discrete spectrum
$(\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\cdots,\lambda_n,\cdots)$ and
$\|A\|_p=[\sum_{n=1}^\infty\lambda_n{}^p]^{1/p}$ is finite. 
For $f\in L_1(G)$ and $s\in S$, let
$\mathcal{F}^±(s)=\int_GU^±(g,s)f(g)\,dg$. 
This is the [operator-valued] Fourier transform of $f$. Let $1<p<2$,
and $q=p/(p-1)$. 
There is a measure $\mu_{q,\sigma}$ on
$ R$ such that for all $f\in L_1(G)\cap L_p(G)$, $$
\left[\int_{-\infty}^\infty\|\mathcal{F}^±(\sigma+it)\|_q{}^q\,d\mu_{q,\sigma}(t)\right]^{1/q}\leq\|f\|_p.
\qquad (1) $$ The
Fourier transform admits a [unique] linear bounded extension over all
of $L_p(G)$ for which (1) holds. 
Furthermore, $\mathcal{ F}^±(s)$ is analytic in $s$.
Analogous results using only the discrete series hold for $p\in[1,2]$. 

The Hausdorff-Young inequality (1), involving the whole strip $ S$ instead of only the line $\text{Re}\,s={\textstyle\frac 1{2}}$, has some curious
consequences. If $f\in L_2(G)$ and $g\in L_p(G)$, $1\leq p<2$, then $f*g\in L_2(G)$ and $\|f*g\|_2\leq A_p\|f\|_2·\|g\|_p$. If $g\in L_2(G)$, then $f*g\in L_q(G)$
for all $q\in\,]2,\infty]$, and $\|f*g\|_q\leq A_q\|f\|_2·\|g\|_2$. Both of these assertions hold trivially for compact groups and fail for the simplest non-compact
Abelian groups, e.g., for the group $ R$. 

This paper is nearly self-contained, and it is very carefully written. It is an important step in realizing the possibilities for detailed harmonic analysis that are
implicit in the Gel'fand-Raikov theorem.


------------------------------------------

Koornwinder, Tom H.(NL-VUAM) 
Jacobi functions and analysis on noncompact semisimple Lie groups. 
Special functions: group theoretical aspects and applications, 1--85, 
Math. Appl., 
Reidel, Dordrecht, 1984. 

From the introduction: "There are many group-theoretic interpretations of Jacobi functions, first as spherical functions on noncompact Riemannian
symmetric spaces of rank one, but also as associated spherical functions, intertwining functions, matrix elements of (representations of) ${\rm SL}(2, R)$ and
spherical functions on certain nonsymmetric Gel'fand pairs. This makes Jacobi functions an ideal subject for the case study of the interactions
between special functions and group theory." 

This paper is a nice survey of this topic, with the personal point of view of the author, and with many published and unpublished results of his own. At the
same time the author has gathered together a great amount of information about the numerous ramifications of the subject. After recalling classical facts first
about the Jacobi functions and the Jacobi transform, then about the
theory of Gel'fand pairs and spherical 
functions, the author studies the Jacobi
functions as spherical functions on rank one symmetric spaces, as associated spherical functions and as functions on certain non-Riemannian symmetric
spaces. He studies further the Abel transform using the Riemann-Liouville and Weyl transforms, and using them, he gives a proof of the Paley-Wiener
theorem for the Jacobi transform. The last parts are devoted to the convolution structure associated with the Jacobi transform, the addition formula and the
dual convolution structure. 

{For the entire collection see MR 85i:22003.}

                                 Reviewed by Jacques Faraut 

-----------------------------------------------------------------

Flensted-Jensen, Mogens; Koornwinder, Tom 
The convolution structure for Jacobi function expansions. 
Ark. Mat. 11, 245--262. (1973). 

G. Gasper:

Let $R_µ{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(x)=F[-µ,µ+\alpha+\beta+1;\alpha+1;(1-x)/2]$, where $F$ is the hypergeometric function. The Jacobi functions (a noncompact
analogue of the Jacobi polynomials $R_n{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(x)$, $n=0,1,2,\cdots$) are defined by
$\phi_\lambda{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(t)=R_{(i\lambda-\rho)/2}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(\cosh 2t)$, where $\rho=\alpha+\beta+1$, $0\leq t<\infty$, and $\lambda$ is a
complex number. H. Bateman's formula [ Partial differential equations of mathematical physics, Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, 1932; Zbl 4, 214; revised edition,
Dover, New York, 1944; MR 6, 86; reprint of first edition, Cambridge Univ. Press, New York, 1959] for the product of two Jacobi polynomials,
$R_n{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(x)R_n{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(y)=\sum_ka_k(x+y)^kR_k{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}((1+xy)/(x+y))$, is extended to the case in which $n$ is not
necessarily an integer, and the extension is used to show that if $\alpha\geq\beta\geq-1/2$, then the product
$\phi_\lambda{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(t_1)\phi_\lambda{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(t_2)$ of two Jacobi functions can be represented as an integral of a Jacobi function
$\phi_\lambda{}^{(\alpha,\beta)}(t_3)$ with a nonnegative kernel. The integral is then used to define a generalized translation operator, the convolution
product of two suitable functions, and to obtain convolution structure results for $\alpha\geq\beta\geq-1/2$ similar to those which were obtained by the
reviewer [Ann. of Math. (2) 95 (1972), 261--280] for
Jacobi series with less restrictive conditions 
on $(\alpha,\beta)$.

                                 ( Reviewed by G. Gasper )
